  "chunk_index": 13,
  "summary": "Bill Everly provides Eileen Bondel with a list of notable individuals, including Lady MacCarty, Sir Stanley Digby (the aviation minister), his secretary Terence O'Roke, an inventor named Hel Eberhard, and Sir Oswald and Lady Kut. When Bondel asks if these people are connected to the \"seven-faced clock,\" Bill feigns ignorance.\n\nBondel then inquires about the Seven Dials Club, which Bill describes as an unrefined, crowded nightclub located in a former slum on Tottenham Court Road. Despite Bill's embarrassment regarding a past altercation with Barbie Saint-Moore involving a lobster, Bondel insists they visit. They take a taxi to 14 Hanstein Street, where Bondel observes a shifty, tall, golden-haired man at the entrance. Inside the smoke-filled basement, they encounter a diverse crowd of foreigners, wealthy women, and sex workers. While upstairs, Bondel recognizes the gambling room guard as Alfred, a former second-class butler from the Chimney House who had left a month prior. After observing the gamblers and spending time dancing and eating, Bondel decides to return home.\n\nThe following morning, Bondel visits her father, Lord Kettlemere, at the Chimney Cottage. He informs her that the county police chief, Melrose, will visit at noon the next day regarding the inquest for Ronnie Devereux, as Bondel discovered the body and is required to testify. Lord Kettlemere also mentions that George Lomax has invited him to the Two-Footed Dragon Church the following week.",
